      • isBillboardModeEnabled

        public boolean isBillboardModeEnabled()
        Determine whether billboard mode is enabled. True if billboard mode is enabled for this geometry, else false See: setBillboardModeEnabled

      • setBillboardModeEnabled

        public void setBillboardModeEnabled(boolean enable)
        Set billboard mode for this geometry, i.e. whether up/right direction in trackable coordinate system should be aligned with up/right of the screenThis is not possible for geometries that were already created with the displayAsBillboard setting (see IMetaioSDK::createGeometryFromImage/createGeometryFromMovie). As opposed to the displayAsBillboard setting, "billboard mode" will always align the X/Y axes of the trackable (seehttps://dev.metaio.com/sdk/getting-started/terminology-and-coordinate- system/) with X/Y of the screen (you can still apply additional translation and rotation of course).
        Parameters:
        enable - Whether to enable or disable billboard mode See: isBillboardModeEnabled

      • isDynamicLightingEnabled

        public boolean isDynamicLightingEnabled()
        Determine whether dynamic lighting affects this geometry. True if lighting enabled for this geometry, else false See: setDynamicLightingEnabled

      • setDynamicLightingEnabled

        public void setDynamicLightingEnabled(boolean enable)
        Set whether this geometry is affected by dynamic lights. If lighting is disabled for a geometry, it will be rendered with 0 lights, i.e. lights will not affect the geometry color.Default is to use lighting.
        Parameters:
        enable - Whether to enable or disable lighting See: IMetaioSDK::createLight

      • setParentGeometry

        public void setParentGeometry(IGeometry parent)
        Attach this share it's transformation.With setParentGeometry you can create a scene graph like structure. All the parents transformation properties will also be applied to the child, this included rotation, translation and scale. Its simpler if you do not set scale as a property, but rather scale the actual model in your content creation tool accordingly.
        Parameters:
        parent - the IGeometry that this one should be attached to. See: getParentGeometry

      • setRenderOrder

        public void setRenderOrder(int level,
                           boolean disableDepth,
                           boolean clearDepth)
        Set the rendering order of the geometry. This method should be used for compositing, e.g. if a geometry should be drawn before or after other geometries. The ordering depends on the value of the level that is passed, the lower levels are drawn before higher levels, which means that a geometry with higher level will be on top of a geometry with lower level.The z-buffer (depth) check can be optionally disabled so that geometries are rendered independent of their real distance from the camera. This is useful when more than one geometries are positioned at same depth (z), or a geometry with greater depth needs to be rendered in front of a geometry with less depth. Note that it works only for simple geometries, e.g a plane or sphere.For complex geometries, clear depth (z-buffer) can be enabled instead of disabling z-buffer check. This would ensure that geometries are rendered in correct order, however, it is an expensive operation and can significantly reduce rendering performance.Note that geometry picking is always based on real distance from the camera. It means that even though a geometry is forced to rendered on top of another geometry (i.e. by disabling z-buffer check and/or enabling clear depth), the background geometry may be picked because it is closer to the camera in reality.
        Parameters:
        level - render order, the higher value means front, default is 0
        disableDepth - true to disable depth test, false to enable (default)
        clearDepth - true to clear depth before rendering, false to disable this (default) See: getRenderOrder
